\begin_layout Subsection
Two mating types
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin by considering a population with two mating types (
\begin_inset Formula $m=2$
\end_inset

).
 As the number of vegetative generations between sex increases so does drift
 on the mating type locus distorting the mating type ratio (Fig.2A).
 This effect decreases for larger population sizes but persists even for
 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

=5000.
 Mating type switching can help restore the mating-type ratio, deeming the
 switching gene advantageous.
 We introduce the switching gene at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{\mu}$
\end_inset

, at low frequency, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{0}$
\end_inset

, and determine the probability of fixation for varying 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 In the absence of selection we expect the switching gene to reach fixation
 with probability equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{0}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Wright1931,Ewens2010"

\end_inset

.
 The fixation probability is a good measure of selection against drift in
 a finite population; the difference between 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{fix}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{0}$
\end_inset

 is indicative of the strength of selection.
 As anticipated, as 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 increases from 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $500$
\end_inset

 we see a sharp increase in the fixation probability for the switching gene
 (Fig.2B).
 Although the effects of drift on the mating type ratio are more pronounced
 for smaller populations and larger g, the probability of fixation is doubled
 contrasted to that expected under drift even for larger populations (
\begin_inset Formula $N>500$
\end_inset

) and small 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We next asked how the switching rate itself, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{s}$
\end_inset

, affects the evolution of the switching locus.
 We gradually introduced mutations conferring an incrementally higher switching
 probability in a quantitative manner (Fig.2C).
 The selection gradient is steep as ps rises from 0 and plateaus with larger
 ps.
 Interestingly, the value of ps at which this occurs, ps*, is lower for
 larger g.
 This initially appears counter to Fig.2B.
 Although a prolonged period of vegetative growth increases selection for
 the switching gene it also provides a larger time window for restoration
 of the sex ratio.
 So despite large values of g correlating with stronger selection for 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{s}$
\end_inset

